rollicking crossover between two of the most popular entertainment properties in comics today! The sudden appearance of a mystical portal between Earth and Thundera leads to chaos, confusion and adventure as Lion-O and Mark rally their troops against the combined might of the villainous Zoltar and Mumm-Ra!
name: Allied Forces

description: In "Domination Pt. 2," a small group of heroes resist the power that has most resident's in it's control. The town, however, is well aware of the threat they pose against it, and those few who hunt down the source of the ultimate evil become the hunted!
name: Domination, part 2

description: An elderly lady-killer, living out his last years in shabby gentility. A mysterious young man wandering aimlessly through an urban wilderness. A chance encounter between two petty lives, each with its own secrets. Insomnia #2 continues Matt Broersma's comics-noir dissection of American society, rendered in uncannily moody two-tone drawings.

Torn apart by unbelievable circumstance, a man stands on the edge of sanity as he tries to come to terms with the horrific events which left him scarred for life. After witnessing his beloved wife's abduction Jack Rackham is beset with guilt, for he could do nothing to stop it. Whatever the creature was, it was most assuredly not of this earth. Many months of tireless searching found naught, but uncovered many more mysterious disappearances. Ridiculed and ignored by the authorities he is forced to take matters into his own hands.

The first issue of a new, ongoing series by cartoonist Michael Kupperman, whose cartooning regularly graces the pages of The Believer and The New Yorker, amongst many other publications. This dense comic magazine includes "Uncle Billy's Drunken, Bitter Guide to the Animal Kingdom," new Pablo Picasso adventures, information on sex blimps and sex holes, an opportunity to meet the hot boy band Boybank, cowboys debating whether comics are serious literature, "Cut-out 'n' Play: Soccer Joust!" and much, much more, including games, text pieces, fake ads and more, all presented with Kupperman's inimitable Dadaist sense of humor. Find out why "Triumph the Insult Comic Dog" creator Robert Smigel says, "Kupperman is hysterical, and a real original," while comedian Andy Richter says, "Kupperman writes a hysterically funny comic book!" This is Kupperman's first comic book since his popular Snake 'n' Bacon's Cartoon Cabaret from HarperCollins in 2000.

person_credits.name: Michael Kupperman
person_credits.role: writer, artist, letterer, colorist, cover, production

description:
"Dawn of Futures Past" by Various Before the Beast Wars, Megatron and his crew of Predacons traveled deep within the inner chambers of Cybertron and stole one of the planet's most guarded secrets.... The Golden Disk! The story that started it all is finally here in this awesome adventure that travels from Cybertron to the far reaches of space. Featuring Optimus Primal, Megatron and the Season 1 cast of Beast Wars, are seen like they never have been before in their pre-earth Cybertronian modes. With an amazing Diamond exclusive cover by Transformers artist Joe Ng and story contributions by Benson Yee and Beast Wars writer Bob Forward.

Released at Botcon 2006
name: Dawn of Futures Past

description: Described as "fictionalized science," this book contains illustrated stories about real scientists and their ideas and works. Ottaviani has taken science history, even lectures, and written them as bite-sized stories. Scientists included are Wolfgang Pauli, Galileo, Isaac Newton, Gottfried Liebnitz, several with Richard Feynman, Bertrand Russell, Albert Einstein, Niels Bohr, Werner Heisenberg and Hans Bethe.

It is the fall of 1888, and a series of grisly murders rock the desperately poorLondonborough ofWhitechapel. While the regular residents of London grow frightened and mistrustful, a group of travelling carnival "freaks" with a dark past prepare to leave a town that has grown increasingly hostile to their presence. As the worlds of the Londoners and the freaks collide, a tragedy unfolds that will forever change London, and the world.

The new issue of MAD is out, and we're campaigning hard for your money! If you elect to buy it, you'll get our spoof ofThe Dark Knight, our look at John McCain's 400-year career, and a special 2-page pull-out poster! All this, plus Spy Vs. Spy, the Fold-In, the MAD Strip Club, Monroe and much, much more! So stop counting yourself as "undecided" and go vote with your dollars buy MAD today!
name: Comedy Before Country Election Issue

description: The critics agree! Tales Designed to Thrizzle #1 is the smash debut of 2005! From Wizard's "Secret Stash" pick of the month to Steven Grant of Comic Book Resources (who says of the first issue, "One of the most entertaining comics I've read in years."), the critics agree! Heidi MacDonald of The Beat says "Folks, this is the funniest thing since Monty Python. I mean it." Tom Spurgeon of The Comics Reporter says, "Really funny... Buy five and leave them in the backseat of your car." Well, for those of you who just can't get enough, the second issue is here! Featuring scary snakes! Delicious bacon! Johnny Silhouette, private eye! The Silver Knight! Create your own adventure with the Space Patrol! Murder She Didn't Write! Are you tired of portraits where the eyes move? And much, much more!

person_credits.name: Michael Kupperman
person_credits.role: writer, artist, letterer, colorist, cover, production

description:
There's no rhyme or reason to the newest issue of MAD as we take a look at the crappy career of a typical rap star! We also mock the Deal or No Deal models and page through some George W. Bush-inspired children's books! Plus Spy Vs. Spy, The Darker Side ofthe Lighter Side, The MAD Fold-In, Planet Tad and much more!

Just remember - into every life, a Lil Wayne must fall!
name: The Rise and Fall of a Rap Star

description:
Overview

Cole Cash (also known as Grifter) is what you might call an arms enthusiast. Paul Newman (not that Paul Newman) is an anti-gun activist. Both are in Vegas for a firearms convention, and each is looking to disrupt the show for his own reason -- Newman wants to wipe firearms off the face of the earth, and Cash wants to steal a state-of-the-art armament known as the Probability Annihilator. Cash has got a dead-accurate eye -- perhaps the best in the world -- to back up his play, but Newman's got something that'll outfire any ol' weapon! Newman's got . . . The Mask!
name: Cleaving Las Vegas, Part 1

description:
Overview

The new fella wearing The Mask has got a major problem with guns. He wants 'em gone, and he'll kill anyone who stands in his way! Including Grifter! As hot as the Las Vegas strip may be, it's about to get hotter!
name: Cleaving Las Vegas, Part 2

description:
Overview

What happens when Gotham's Clown Prince of Crime discovers a thousand-year-old relic that will make him invincible? Unfortunately, Batman is about to find out! Be there for the first meeting between two of comics' greatest madmen, as the Joker and the Mask join forces (literally) to give the Dark Knight a run for his money! Don't miss out on the mayhem! Co-published with DC Comics.
name: Issue 1

description:
Overview

After finding the all-powerful Mask, the Joker is transformed into Joker/Mask, and he's becoming a TV superstar while wreaking havoc all over Gotham City! Making matters even worse, Batman is nowhere to be found! Who knows how far this will go? Co-published with DC Comics.

Overview

The new "Joker/Mask" show is a big hit in prime time, but not everyone is happy. Harley wants her old Mr. J back, and she enlists Poison Ivy to help her...but Ivy has plans of her own. And when Joker/Mask figures out he's been duped, he's gonna be one unhappy clown. Harley, Ivy, and all of Gotham City had better get ready for the explosive finale! Co-published with DC Comics.

1993 Annual that originally came sealed with a card. All 1993 Marvel annuals introduced a new character. The card included featured the new character Eradikator. This annual contains three stories and five pin-ups.

The pin-ups included were by Andy Wildman and George Wildman; Ken Branch and Jason Temujin; Ken Branch; Scott Kolins and Ken branch; and McDuffy and Josef Rubenstein. The first four were colored by Sue McTeigue. The last pin-up was colored by Kevin Somers.

Death Metal

by Pat Mills, Tony Skinner, Dave Hoover, Ken Lopz, and Daisy Deputhod

When Frank's discovers that one of his war buddies has been killed, Punisher uncovers plot to do away with the rest of his friend's family. Punisher must protect the next victim before Eradikator 4 gets to him.

Preacher

by Stephen Grant, Shawn McManus, Ken Lopez, John and Kaalisz

A New high-tech gun has been designed and Punisher must stop it from falling into the wrong hands.

Tracers

by Chuck Dixon, Dale Eaglesham, Pat Redding, and Richard Starkings

Knocking off gangsters isn't always easy. Punisher is pursued by gangsters after a recent hit.
name: Eradikation
